I started this task by making a function to read files. I made it so that the answer file is always read. I then made it so that the input file being called is compared to it. Upon each deviation from the original, I would subtract one point off and return 100 minus the total off. After that, I had to devise a way to sort all of the values. I was thinking about being fancy and going for a well-known sorting algorithm but ultimately decided on an algorithm that searches for the max value in each iteration, adds it to the final array, and renders the element taken unusable. After implementing this, I moved onto the grade printer. Inside of this, I took the array and printed the student name, grade, and their grade number in letter form (in the form of another function). After that, I attempted the extra credit. To start, I looked at the line differences between the answer and students and determined which mistakes were ones that would prevent the program from compiling. After that, I added it to the initial file reading part and assigned it -1 if it did not compile. Back in main, I kept note of which ones did not compile and used a conditional to deal with it accordingly. I also have a bunch of debugging info present, like printArr which I used quite a few times to debug certain issues. After that, I realized that the output must be written to another file, so I added those functionalities within the grade printer function.
